A grocer sells potatoes, mushrooms and carrots.

\begin{parts}
\item A customer buys 3 kg of mushrooms at \$1.04 per kg and 4 kg of carrots at \$1.28 per kg.

Calculate the total cost.

\AnswerLine[][\$]
\Marks{2}

\item In one week, the ratio of the masses of vegetables sold by the grocer is

\centerline{potatoes : mushrooms : carrots = 11 : 8 : 6.}

\begin{subparts}
\item Work out the mass of mushrooms sold as a percentage of the total mass.

\AnswerLine[][\%]
\Marks{2}

\item The total mass of potatoes, mushrooms and carrots sold is 1500 kg.

Find the mass of carrots the grocer sells this week.

\AnswerLine[][kg]
\Marks{2}

\item The profit the grocer makes selling 1 kg of carrots is \$0.75 .

Find the total profit the grocer makes selling carrots this week.

\AnswerLine[][\$]
\Marks{1}

\item On the last day of the week, the grocer reduces the price of 1 kg of potatoes by 8\% to \$1.15 .

Calculate the original price of 1 kg of potatoes.

\AnswerLine[][\$]
\Marks{2}

\end{subparts}

\item The grocer buys 620 kg of onions, correct to the nearest 20 kg.
He packs them into bags each containing 5 kg of onions, correct to the nearest 1 kg.

Calculate the upper bound for the number of bags of onions that he packs.

\AnswerLine[][]
\Marks{3}

\end{parts}

